# Anubis
# AI bot firewall exposed as a Traefik ForwardAuth service.
# Docs: https://anubis.techaro.lol/

# Docker image tag. Anubis does not publish a major-version floating tag,
# so this defaults to `latest`. Pin a specific version (e.g. 1.20.0) here
# if you prefer a reproducible deployment.
IMAGE_TAG=latest

# Host bind and container paths.
BIND_ADDR=127.0.0.1
BIND_PORT=8923
HOST_CONFIG_DIR=./config
HOST_DATA_DIR=./data

# Compose feature variant. Three values are supported:
#   default            - no Traefik wiring; Anubis is reachable only on
#                        the localhost bind for debugging. Effectively
#                        useless in production but kept for parity with
#                        the other stacks in this repo.
#   traefik            - (default for anubis) Anubis is attached to the
#                        shared `traefik` Docker network so the forwardAuth
#                        middleware in traefik/config/dynamic/anubis.yml.dist
#                        can reach it at http://anubis:8923. No public
#                        hostname is registered for Anubis itself; the
#                        challenge is served on the same host as the
#                        protected application (in-site challenge).
#   traefik_exposed    - Anubis is also registered as its own router on
#                        the public hostname in TRAEFIK_HOST. This is the
#                        cross-origin / separate-host flow, where the
#                        challenge page is served from Anubis's own
#                        origin and the user is redirected back to the
#                        protected host on success. Requires PUBLIC_URL,
#                        REDIRECT_DOMAINS, and COOKIE_DOMAIN (see the
#                        "Cross-origin (traefik_exposed) variant"
#                        section below).
#
# Note: anubis defaults to `traefik` rather than `default` (which is
# the repo-wide default) because Anubis is fundamentally a forwardAuth
# service: the `default` variant produces a container with no Traefik
# wiring and no useful function. See anubis/README.md for the
# rationale and the per-stack path-exclusion guide.
COMPOSE_VARIANT=traefik

# Traefik network. Must match the network the Traefik stack joined when
# you ran `docker network create`.
TRAEFIK_NETWORK=traefik

# Optional challenge difficulty. Anubis applies its own default when unset.
# Increase to slow down scrapers; decrease to make the challenge easier.
#DIFFICULTY=4

# Container logging.
LOG_MAX_SIZE=5m
LOG_MAX_FILE=5

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Required env vars for the in-site flow (default traefik variant)
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# PUBLIC_URL is required even in the default in-site flow. Without it
# the api/check endpoint returns a 22-byte "Authorization required" body
# on every CHALLENGE decision, and users are stuck on a bare 401 instead
# of being redirected to the challenge page. It also enables the
# post-challenge redirect target. Set it to the public origin that
# Anubis should use as the challenge host's base URL. In a single-host
# in-site deployment, this is the protected application's public origin.
#PUBLIC_URL=https://app.example.com

# COOKIE_DOMAIN scopes the Anubis cookie across subdomains. Required
# when Anubis protects more than one subdomain (e.g. anubis shared
# across app.example.com, ci.example.com, woodpecker.example.com).
# A leading dot means the cookie is shared across all subdomains of
# the parent domain, e.g. `.example.com` covers app.example.com and
# ci.example.com. Without it, users would have to solve the challenge
# on every subdomain.
#COOKIE_DOMAIN=.example.com

# REDIRECT_DOMAINS is a security allowlist. After a successful
# challenge, Anubis only redirects the browser to a hostname that
# appears in this list. Without it, Anubis would behave as an open
# redirector and could be abused for phishing. Must list every
# public hostname Anubis protects, for example:
#   REDIRECT_DOMAINS=app.example.com,ci.example.com,woodpecker.example.com
#REDIRECT_DOMAINS=

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Cross-origin (traefik_exposed) variant
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# The variables in this section are only needed when
# COMPOSE_VARIANT=traefik_exposed. With the default in-site flow
# (COMPOSE_VARIANT=traefik) Anubis is not exposed on a public hostname
# of its own and these values are unused. See the "Using the
# traefik_exposed variant" section in anubis/README.md and the
# tracking issue for the design and security notes.
# Tracking: https://git.skobk.in/skobkin/docker-stacks/issues/333
#
# Standard 7-label Traefik wiring (read by compose.features.yml).
# TRAEFIK_HOST has no default in compose.features.yml -- if unset the
# Traefik rule becomes `Host(`)` and Traefik fails to start the router
# with a clear error. Fill in the value in .env from this template.

# Public hostname Anubis itself is reachable on. Traefik issues a
# Let's Encrypt certificate for this host and serves Anubis at
# https://<TRAEFIK_HOST>/. Required for traefik_exposed.
#TRAEFIK_HOST=anubis.example.com

# Comma-separated Traefik entrypoints. Defaults to the shared
# `websecure` entrypoint defined by the traefik stack. Override only
# if you have a non-standard entrypoint layout.
#TRAEFIK_ENTRYPOINTS=websecure

# Middleware on the Anubis host router. The repo default
# `default-access@file` resolves to whatever is uncommented in
# traefik/config/dynamic/default-access.yml.dist -- either a private
# ipAllowList (LAN ranges) or a public ipAllowList (0.0.0.0/0, ::/0).
# For a public Anubis challenge host you almost certainly want the
# public variant active in default-access.yml.dist, or a different
# middleware (e.g. public-access@file). A private default-access on
# the Anubis router would 403 every browser before the challenge can
# run. This variable is shared with every other Traefik-fronted stack
# in this repo; the value below is the default and is the same as
# every other stack -- the Anubis-specific decision is which variant
# of default-access is active in the dynamic config.
#TRAEFIK_ACCESS_POLICY=default-access@file
